{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"61f85239-185e-436b-8cbd-f3eafb81e3d2","content":"In .NET MAUI, you configure platform lifecycle events in your `MauiProgram.cs` using `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity => { /* runs on pause */ })\n        .OnStop(activity => { /* runs on stop */ }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* runs on background */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;`\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code separate.\n- Each platform exposes its native events (e.g., `OnResume`, `OnDestroy` on Android; `WillEnterForeground`, `WillTerminate` on iOS).\n- The handlers receive the native platform objects (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS), so you can call platform APIs directly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"15d79d82-5bab-4e75-a381-e5805c06ff20","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development. I can answer this directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":352,"requestId":"1439:147A9A:6BC9AEA:74186CD:6A03CC84"},"id":"a1c61d5c-88e6-4358-ba45-f90348626bd0","timestamp":"2026-05-13T00:57:48.361Z","parentId":"6a8af5a9-ee26-45bc-abda-55cbca75de51"}
